                <p dir=3D"ltr"><span>Permutation and Combination are the mo=
st fundamental concepts in mathematics related to picking items from a grou=
p or set.  </span></p><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>Permutation is the arrangem=
ent of items in which the order of selection matters.</span></li><li value=
=3D"2"><span>Combination is selecting items without considering order.</spa=
n></li><li value=3D"3"><span>For example, in the below diagram, PQ and QP a=
re different in permutation but same in combination. Therefore we have more=
 permutations than combinations.</span></li></ul><figure class=3D"image"><i=
mg src=3D"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/uploads/20240521154648=
/Permutation-an-Combination.webp" alt=3D"Permutation-an-Combination" width=
=3D"801" height=3D"400"><figcaption>Permutations and Combinations</figcapti=
on></figure><h2 id=3D"permutation" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Permutat=
ion Meaning</span></h2><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>Permutation is the way of arran=
ging items where order is important.  For example, if we have two component=
s A and B, then they can be arranged in these ways, {</span><i><em class=3D=
"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic">AB</em></i><span> and </span><i><em class=3D"G=
FGEditorTheme__textItalic">BA</em></i><span>}. </span></p><p dir=3D"ltr" st=
yle=3D"text-align: start;"><span>Permutation is represented as </span><b><s=
up><strong>n </strong></sup></b><b><strong>P</strong></b><b><sub><strong>r<=
/strong></sub></b><span> .</span></p><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>Where </span=
><b><strong>=E2=80=98r=E2=80=99</strong></b><span> is the permutation size,=
 like how many components you have to choose.</span></li><li value=3D"2"><s=
pan>Whereas </span><b><strong>=E2=80=98n=E2=80=99</strong></b><span> is the=
 total number of components present.</span></li></ul><blockquote><p dir=3D"=
ltr"><span>For example, let n =3D 3 (A, B, and C) and r =3D 2 (All permutat=
ions of size 2). </span><br><span>Then there are </span><b><sup><strong>3</=
strong></sup></b><b><strong>P</strong></b><b><sub><strong>2</strong></sub><=
/b><span> such permutations, which is equal to 6. </span><br><span>These si=
x permutations are AB, AC, BA, BC, CA, and CB. </span><br><span>The six per=
mutations of A, B, and C taken three at a time are shown in the image added=
 below:</span></p><img src=3D"https://media.geeksforgeeks.org/wp-content/up=
loads/20230502131208/Permutation-Combination-4.webp" alt=3D"Permutation of =
Two elements out of A, B, and C" width=3D"inherit" height=3D"inherit" loadi=
ng=3D"lazy"></blockquote><h3 id=3D"permutation-formula" style=3D"text-align=
:left"><span>Permutation Formula</span></h3><p dir=3D"ltr"><a href=3D"https=
://www.geeksforgeeks.org/maths/permutation/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noope=
ner"><span>Permutation formula</span></a><span> is used to find the number =
of ways to pick </span><b><strong>=E2=80=98r=E2=80=99</strong></b><span> th=
ings out of </span><b><strong>=E2=80=98n=E2=80=99</strong></b><span> differ=
ent things in a specific order, and replacement is not allowed. The formula=
