of Permutations Formula</span></h3><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>Permutation is sele=
cting r distinct objects from n objects without replacement, and where the =
order of selection is important. By the fundamental theorem of counting and=
 the definition of permutation, we get</span></p><blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr"=
 style=3D"text-align: left;"><b><strong>P (n, r) =3D n . (n-1) . (n-2) . (n=
-3). &nbsp;. . . &nbsp;.(n-(r+1))</strong></b></p></blockquote><p dir=3D"lt=
r"><span>By multiplying and dividing above with (n-r)! =3D (n-r).(n-r-1).(n=
-r-2). &nbsp;. . . &nbsp;.3. 2. 1, we get</span></p><blockquote><p dir=3D"l=
tr"><span>P (n, r) =3D [n.(n=E2=88=921).(n=E2=88=922)=E2=80=A6.(nr+1)[(n=E2=
=88=92r)(n=E2=88=92r=E2=88=921)(n-r)!] / (n-r)!</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><b=
><strong>=E2=87=92 P (n, r) =3D n!/(n=E2=88=92r)!</strong></b></p></blockqu=
ote><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>Thus, the formula for P (n, r) is derived.</span><=
/p><h3 id=3D"derivation-of-combinations-formula" style=3D"text-align:left">=
<span>Derivation of Combinations Formula</span></h3><p dir=3D"ltr"><span>Co=
mbination is choosing r items out of n items when the order of selection is=
 of no importance. Its formula is calculated as,</span></p><blockquote><p d=
ir=3D"ltr"><span>C(n, r) =3D Total Number of Permutations /Number of ways t=
o arrange r different objects.&nbsp;</span><br><span>[Since by the fundamen=
tal theorem of counting, we know that number of ways to arrange r different=
